\section{The Basic Idea of Limits}{}{}


Consider the function:
\[
f(x) = \frac{x^2 - 3x + 2}{x-2}
\]
The domain of this function is $(-\infty, 2)\cup(2,\infty)$. The
notion of \textit{limits} will help us answer the following question:
Does there exist a continuous function on $\R$ that is equal to $f(x)$
on $(-\infty, 2)\cup(2,\infty)$?
\begin{tikzpicture}
	\begin{axis}[width=190pt,axis x line=middle, axis y line=center, tick align=outside]
	  \addplot+[mark=none,smooth] {(\x^2-3\x+2)/(\x-2)};
	\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
